in Toronto, a city with much denser clusters of venues.¶

when there is a number of venues. I will work with their parameters to develop functions that perform multiple¶

# function that extracts the category of the venue
def get_categories(row):
    try:
        categories_list = row['categories']
    except:
        categories_list = row['venue.categories']
        
    if len(categories_list) == 0:
        return None
    else:
        return categories_list[0]['name']

def getVenuesSearch(query, latitudes, longitudes, radius = 15000, LIMIT = 50):
    
    
    search_results_all = pd.DataFrame(columns=['id','address', 'lat', 'lng'])
    i = 0
    
    for latitude, longitude in zip(latitudes, longitudes):
        print('centroid: ', i, latitude, longitude)
            
        # create the API request URL
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/search?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}&query={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            latitude, 
            longitude, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT,
            query)
        print(url) # display URL
                  
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()
        search_results = results['response']['venues']
        search_results_df = pd.json_normalize(search_results) # flatten JSON

        # filter columns
        filtered_columns = ['id', 'location.address', 'location.lat', 'location.lng']
        nearby_search_venues = search_results_df.loc[:, filtered_columns]

        # clean columns
        nearby_search_venues.columns = [col.split(".")[-1] for col in nearby_search_venues.columns]
        
        search_results_all = pd.concat([search_results_all, nearby_search_venues])
        print('search_results_all size: ', search_results_all.shape)
        i = i +1

    search_results_all = search_results_all.drop_duplicates(subset='id', ignore_index=True)
    print('search_results_all size: ', search_results_all.shape)
          
    return(search_results_all)

def getRecommendedIntent(intent, latitudes, longitudes, radius = 15000, LIMIT = 50):
    
    # Intent: One of: food, breakfast, brunch, lunch, coffee, dinner, dessert, drinks, shopping, fun, sights. 
    # Specifies the top-level intent for a search.
    
    
    recommended_all = pd.DataFrame(columns=['id', 'name', 'categories', 'address', 'lat', 'lng'])
    i = 0
    
    for latitude, longitude in zip(latitudes, longitudes):
        print('centroid: ', i, latitude, longitude)
            
        # create the API request URL
         
        
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/search/recommendations?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&intent={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            latitude, 
            longitude, 
            radius, 
            intent,
            LIMIT)
        print(url) # display URL
            
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()
        recommended = results['response']['group']['results']
        recommended_df = pd.json_normalize(recommended) # flatten JSON

        # filter columns
        filtered_columns = ['venue.id', 'venue.name', 'venue.categories', 'venue.location.address', 'venue.location.lat', 'venue.location.lng']
        recommended_venues = recommended_df.loc[:, filtered_columns]

        # filter the category for each row
        recommended_venues['venue.categories'] = recommended_venues.apply(get_categories, axis=1)

        # clean columns
        recommended_venues.columns = [col.split(".")[-1] for col in recommended_venues.columns]
        
        recommended_all = pd.concat([recommended_all, recommended_venues])
        print('recommended_all size: ', recommended_all.shape)
        i = i +1

    recommended_all = recommended_all.drop_duplicates(subset='id', ignore_index=True)
    print('recommended_all size: ', recommended_all.shape)
          
    return(recommended_all)

def getRecommended(latitudes, longitudes, radius = 35000, query = 'Starbucks', LIMIT = 25):
    
    # 43.5 km = 27 miles, distance between farthest Starbucks with rating >= 8.0
    # 20 km = 12 miles;  35 km = 22 miles
    
    Starbucks_Rating = pd.DataFrame(columns=['id', 'name', 'categories', 'address', 'lat', 'lng'])
    recommended_all = pd.DataFrame(columns=['id', 'name', 'categories', 'address', 'lat', 'lng'])
    i = 0
    
    for latitude, longitude in zip(latitudes, longitudes):
        print('centroid: ', i, latitude, longitude)
            
        # create the API request URL
        
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/search/recommendations?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&query={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            latitude, 
            longitude, 
            radius, 
            query,
            LIMIT)
        print(url) # display URL     
            
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()
        recommended = results['response']['group']['results']
        recommended_df = pd.json_normalize(recommended) # flatten JSON

        # filter columns
        filtered_columns = ['venue.id', 'venue.name', 'venue.categories', 'venue.location.address', 'venue.location.lat', 'venue.location.lng']
        recommended_venues = recommended_df.loc[:, filtered_columns]

        # filter the category for each row
        recommended_venues['venue.categories'] = recommended_venues.apply(get_categories, axis=1)

        # clean columns
        recommended_venues.columns = [col.split(".")[-1] for col in recommended_venues.columns]
        recommended_all = pd.concat([recommended_all, recommended_venues])
        
        print('recommended_all size: ', recommended_all.shape)
        i = i +1

    Starbucks_Rating = recommended_all[recommended_all.duplicated(subset='id')]
    # Keep row if duplicated, meaning recommended Starbucks appears even though it may be farther away, so high rating
    Starbucks_Rating = Starbucks_Rating.drop_duplicates(subset='id', ignore_index=True)
    # Now remove any duplicates
    
    recommended_all = recommended_all.drop_duplicates(subset='id', ignore_index=True)
    
    print('Starbucks_Rating size: ', Starbucks_Rating.shape)
    print('recommended_all size: ', recommended_all.shape)
          
    return(Starbucks_Rating, recommended_all)

#### While Search/ Recommendations isn't time of day sensitive as is Venues/ Explore, it is very sensitive to your location.
#### The results list will begin with the top venues close to you & high ratings, followed by recommended venues that are still close but lower ratings, 
#### and then top rated sites that may be at the edge of your search radius.

### St. Louis spans approximately 23 miles North-South & 25 miles East-West with a population of 2 million and greater metropolitan area population of 2.8 million.

#### Toronto covers an area of 630 square kilometres (243 sq mi), population of 3 million and the greater Toronto area population of 6 million.
#### with a maximum northsouth distance of 21 kilometres (13 mi)
#### and a maximum eastwest distance of 43 km (27 mi). It has a 46-kilometre (29 mi) long waterfront shoreline, on the northwestern shore of Lake Ontario.

# 18.6 miles = 30 km

# getRecommended returns 2 dataframes. The recommended_starbucks df is all recommended stores from 4 different search locations with duplicates removed.

# The starbucks_rating df will KEEP only rows that are duplicated, meaning recommended Starbucks appearing farther away, at edges of one search radius, so
# appearing lower in results list, will appear higher in results when the search is repeated at coordinates that are closer to it. A store that only 
# made it on one recommended list, made it because it was very close to the search coordinates. 
# After single entries are removed, we are left with a list of the most highly rated stores, but may also have 2 or 3 entries due to 4 searches.
# The last step is to remove the duplicates of these top rated stores.

starbucks_rating, recommended_starbucks = getRecommended(latitudes=coordinates[:, 0], longitudes=coordinates[:, 1])

# venue_details_rating

For each Starbucks id listed, get Venue Details which includes rating.¶

This is a Premium endpoint. Restrictions apply based on your account type.¶

The Foursquare API has a limit of 950 Regular API Calls per day and 50 Premium API Calls per day.¶

To Reduce the number of Premium API Calls we first looked for Recommendations for Starbucks¶

We then filtered out the locations with lower ratings based on them not showing up in Recommendations list from¶

somewhat more distant starting coordinates.¶

Now we can run a Venues Details on the Starbucks passing our Recommmendations criteria and extract the actual¶

Foursquare Customers Ratings.¶

In [63]:
for i in range(0,len(starbucks_id)):
    venue_id = starbucks_id.iloc[i]

    url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/{}?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}'.format(
        venue_id,
        CLIENT_ID, 
        CLIENT_SECRET, 
        VERSION)
    print(url) # display URL
    
    results = requests.get(url).json()
    My_StL_Rating = results['response']['venue']['rating']
    starbucks_rating.loc[i, 'rating'] = My_StL_Rating
    print('My_StL_Rating: ', My_StL_Rating)

Modified recommended search for highest ratings.¶

Change search radius from 35km to 15km; Limit from 25 to 7 and increase search coordinates to 6.¶

This keeps distance from search coordinates a major factor in results found and limits results to the few very best matches for a coordinate.¶

Increase coordinates ( Cluster Centers ) to improve coverage. Duplicates from overlapping search circles are removed.¶

In [72]:
def getRecommendedK(latitudes, longitudes, radius = 15000, query = 'Starbucks', LIMIT = 7):
    
    
    recommended_all = pd.DataFrame(columns=['id', 'name', 'categories', 'address', 'lat', 'lng'])
    i = 0
    
    for latitude, longitude in zip(latitudes, longitudes):
        print('centroid: ', i, latitude, longitude)
            
        # create the API request URL
        
        url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/search/recommendations?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&query={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            latitude, 
            longitude, 
            radius, 
            query,
            LIMIT)
        print(url) # display URL     
            
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url).json()
        recommended = results['response']['group']['results']
        recommended_df = pd.json_normalize(recommended) # flatten JSON

        # filter columns
        filtered_columns = ['venue.id', 'venue.name', 'venue.categories', 'venue.location.address', 'venue.location.lat', 'venue.location.lng']
        recommended_venues = recommended_df.loc[:, filtered_columns]

        # filter the category for each row
        recommended_venues['venue.categories'] = recommended_venues.apply(get_categories, axis=1)

        # clean columns
        recommended_venues.columns = [col.split(".")[-1] for col in recommended_venues.columns]
        recommended_all = pd.concat([recommended_all, recommended_venues])
        print('recommended_all size: ', recommended_all.shape)
        i = i +1

    recommended_all = recommended_all.drop_duplicates(subset='id', ignore_index=True)
    print('recommended_all size: ', recommended_all.shape)
          
    return(recommended_all)
